lensing measurements from the fourth data release of the Kilo-
Degree Survey (KiDS-1000). These measurements extend the radial
acceleration relation (RAR), traditionally measured using galaxy
rotation curves, by 2 decades in g$_{obs}$ into the low-
acceleration regime beyond the outskirts of the observable
galaxy. We compare our RAR measurements to the predictions of
two modified gravity (MG) theories: modified Newtonian dynamics
and Verlinde's emergent gravity (EG). We find that the measured
relation between g$_{obs}$ and g$_{bar}$ agrees well with the MG
predictions. In addition, we find a difference of at least
6{\ensuremath{\sigma}} between the RARs of early- and late-type
galaxies (split by S{\'e}rsic index and u {\ensuremath{-}} r
